Column Comment.0: INFORMATION ITEM SUBTYPE: the type of information item. May be one of Thevalid types of Information item as defined by check constraints.
Column Comment.1: INFORMATION ITEM ID: The unique identifier for an information item.
Column Comment.2: ABSTRACT: A short textual description about the information contained in thisinformation item, often as provided in accompanying meta data.
Column Comment.3: ACCEPTED DATE: The date of acceptance of the resource (e.g. thesis by university,or article by journal etc.). Equivalent to the Dublin Core element dc:dateAccepted.
Column Comment.4: ACCESS CONDITION DESCRIPTION: a textual description of the access conditionsthat must be met in order to gain access to the information content or a physicalrepresentation of an object. For example, written permission from the author orasupervisor may be required, or a form filled out and approved. This may alsocapture conditions applied because of legislation or privacy requirements.
Column Comment.5: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y or N flag indicating whether this row of data is currentlyeither active/valid (Y) or inactive/invalid (N).
Column Comment.6: AVAILABLE DATE: Date that the resource will become or did become available.Equivalent to the Dublin Core element dc:available.
Column Comment.7: COORD ACQUISITION: identifies an assembly of coordinate data that must begrouped together. It should be acquired together at the same time, from the samesource, using the same method and at the same accuracy. May be used to indicatethe level of accuracy of a set of coordinates.
Column Comment.8: COPYRIGHT DATE: The date that statement of copyright was received on thisresource. Equivalent to the Dublin Core element dc:dateCopyrighted.
Column Comment.9: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.10: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.11: GEOGRAPHIC COORDINATE SYSTEM IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for thegeographic coordinate system that the spatial component of this information item isrelated to.
Column Comment.12: GROUP INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating that this information item is included in atleast one information item group. Use this flag to improve query performance andavoid outer joins.
Column Comment.13: ISSUE DATE: The date that this resource was formally issued, particularly adocument or map, although applicable to other kinds of information item as well.Equivalent to the Dublin Core element dc:issued.
Column Comment.14: INFORMATION ITEM CATEGORY: the category of information item, such as May beAcquisition support products, trace products etc.
Column Comment.15: ITEM SUB CATEGORY: THE SUB CATEGORY OF INFORMATION OR PHYSICALITEM. MAY BE ACQUISITION SUPPORT DATA ETC.
Column Comment.16: LOCAL COORDINATE SYSTEM IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for the localcoordinate system, such as a local grid system (ATS, STS, MTS etc) to which thesecoordinates have been referenced. Coordinates that are referenced to a localcoordinate system are usually surveyed relative to the local system using metes andbounds or local survey references; maintaining the position of each point relative toits referenced local system is very important to survey accuracy.
Column Comment.17: MAP COORDINATE SYSTEM IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for the mappingcoordinate system that the spatial component of this information item is related to.
Column Comment.18: MAXIMUM LATITUDE: The maximum latitude of the bounding box enclosing theinformation item.
Column Comment.19: MAXIMUM LONGITUDE: The max longitude of the bounding box enclosing theinformation item
Column Comment.20: MINIMUM LATITUDE: The minimum latitude of the bounding box enclosing theinformation item.
Column Comment.21: MINIMUM LONGITUDE: The minimum longitude of the bounding box enclosing g theinformation item.
Column Comment.22: MODIFIED DATE: the last date on which the resource was modified. Equivalent tothe Dublin Core element dc:modified.
Column Comment.23: ORIGIN DATE on which the item was originated (created)
Column Comment.24: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.25: PUBLISHED DATE: the date that this information item was published. Can be storedto date or time level, as needed.
Column Comment.26: PURPOSE: a narrative description of the purpose for the information item, usually asprovided in accompanying meta data.
Column Comment.27: REFERENCE NUMBER: a reference number by which this item may be known by,such as a file number assigned by a department or agency.
Column Comment.28: REMARK: Narrative remarks about this row of data.
Column Comment.29: SECURITY DESCRIPTION: A narrative description of the additional informationabout restrictions on handing data. May relate to national security or legal restrictionrequirements. For more detailed and specific information about who can access thedata or information, use the Entitlements module.
Column Comment.30: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.31: SOURCE DOCUMENT: Where relevant, the source document that provided theorigin for this object. For example, could be the source document for a thesaurus ofterms.
Column Comment.32: SUBMITTED DATE: The date that a resource was submitted (such as a thesis orarticle). Equivalent to the Dublin Core element dc:dateSubmitted.
Column Comment.33: TIME PERIOD DESCRIPTION: A narrative description of the time period for thisinformation item.
Column Comment.34: TITLE: The title of the item
Column Comment.35: USE CONDITIONS: Restrictions and legal prerequisites for using the data set afteraccess has been granted. These include any use constraints applied to ensure theprotection of privacy or intellectual property and any special restrictions or limitationson using the dataset.
Column Comment.36: VERSION NUMBER: The version number of the information item, in the event thatmultiple versions of the same information item may be captured. use the table RMINFO ITEM ORIGIN to track the lineage between versions (to do this, each versionmust be stored as an information item).
Column Comment.37: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.38: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.39: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.40: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.41: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.42: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.43: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
